# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: fwupd
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:fwupd/acpi] Internally, ACPI advertises the available components and their functions to the operating system kernel using instruction lists ("methods") provided through the system firmware (UEFI or BIOS), which the kernel parses.
[src:fwupd/acpi] ACPI then executes the desired operations written in *ACPI Machine Language* (such as the initialization of hardware components) using an embedded minimal virtual machine.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Intel, Microsoft and Toshiba originally developed the standard, while HP, Huawei and Phoenix also participated later.
[src:fwupd/acpi] In October 2013, ACPI Special Interest Group (ACPI SIG), the original developers of the ACPI standard, agreed to transfer all assets to the UEFI Forum, in which all future development will take place.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The latest version of the standard 6.6 was released in 13 May 2025.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The firmware-level ACPI has three main components: the ACPI tables, the ACPI BIOS, and the ACPI registers.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The ACPI BIOS generates ACPI tables and loads ACPI tables into main memory.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Much of the firmware ACPI functionality is provided in bytecode of *ACPI Machine Language* (*AML*), a Turing-complete, domain-specific low-level language, stored in the ACPI tables.
[src:fwupd/acpi] To make use of the ACPI tables, the operating system must have an interpreter for the AML bytecode.
[src:fwupd/acpi] A reference AML interpreter implementation is provided by the *ACPI Component Architecture* (*ACPICA*).
[src:fwupd/acpi] At the BIOS development time, AML bytecode is compiled from *ACPI Source Language* (*ASL*) code.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The **ACPI Component Architecture** (**ACPICA**), mainly written by Intel's engineers, provides an open-source platform-independent reference implementation of the operating system–related ACPI code.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The ACPICA code is used by Linux, Haiku, ArcaOS and FreeBSD, which supplement it with their operating-system specific code.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The first revision of the ACPI specification was released in December 1996, supporting 16, 24 and 32-bit addressing spaces.
[src:fwupd/acpi] It was not until August 2000 that ACPI received 64-bit address support as well as support for multiprocessor workstations and servers with revision 2.0.
[src:fwupd/acpi] In 1999, then Microsoft CEO Bill Gates stated in an e-mail that Linux would benefit from ACPI without them having to do work and suggested to make it Windows-only.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Released in June 2009, revision 4.0 of the ACPI specification added various new features to the design; most notable are the USB 3.0 support, logical processor idling support, and x2APIC support.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Initially ACPI was exclusive to x86 architecture; Revision 5.0 of the ACPI specification was released in December 2011, which added the ARM architecture support.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The revision 5.1 was released in July 2014.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The latest revision 6.6, which was released in May 2025, added the RISC-V support.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Microsoft's Windows 98 was the first operating system to implement ACPI, but its implementation was somewhat buggy or incomplete, although some of the problems associated with it were caused by the first-generation ACPI hardware.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Other operating systems, including later versions of Windows, macOS (x86 macOS only), eComStation, ArcaOS, FreeBSD (since FreeBSD 5.0), NetBSD (since NetBSD 1.6), OpenBSD (since OpenBSD 3.8), HP-UX, OpenVMS, Linux, GNU/Hurd and PC versions of Solaris, have at least some support for ACPI.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Some newer operating systems, like Windows Vista, require the computer to have an ACPI-compliant BIOS, and since Windows 8, the S0ix/Modern Standby state was implemented.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Windows operating systems use acpi.sys to access ACPI events.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The 2.4 series of the Linux kernel had only minimal support for ACPI, with better support implemented (and enabled by default) from kernel version 2.6.0 onwards.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Old ACPI BIOS implementations tend to be quite buggy, and consequently are not supported by later operating systems.
[src:fwupd/acpi] For example, Windows 2000, Windows XP, and Windows Server 2003 only use ACPI if the BIOS date is after January 1, 1999.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Similarly, Linux kernel 2.6 may not use ACPI if the BIOS date is before January 1, 2001.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Linux-based operating systems can provide handling of ACPI events via acpid.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Once an OSPM-compatible operating system activates ACPI, it takes exclusive control of all aspects of power management and device configuration.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The OSPM implementation must expose an ACPI-compatible environment to device drivers, which exposes certain system, device and processor states.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The specification also defines a *Legacy* state: the state of an operating system which does not support ACPI.
[src:fwupd/acpi] In this state, the hardware and power are not managed via ACPI, effectively disabling ACPI.
[src:fwupd/acpi] For describing the idle states of groupings of components (e.g. a package containing several cores), the _LPI (low power idle) method is used.
[src:fwupd/acpi] This should not be confused with Intel's private LPIT table, used to describe S0ix sleep in package C10 or PCH SLP_S0 state.
[src:fwupd/acpi] While a device or processor operates (D0 and C0, respectively), it can be in one of several power-performance states.
[src:fwupd/acpi] These states are implementation-dependent.
[src:fwupd/acpi] P0 is always the highest-performance state, with P1 to P*n* being successively lower-performance states.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The total number of states is device or processor dependent, but can be no greater than 16.
[src:fwupd/acpi] P-states have become known as SpeedStep in Intel processors, as PowerNow! or Cool'n'Quiet in AMD processors, and as PowerSaver in VIA processors.
[src:fwupd/acpi] See Dynamic frequency scaling § Autonomous frequency scaling for a brief description of a newer control method based on the ACPI Collaborative Processor Performance Control (CPPC).
[src:fwupd/acpi] This new method allows hundreds of possible states, and for the processor to autonomously to choose from a given range of states.
[src:fwupd/acpi] ACPI-compliant systems interact with hardware through either a "Function Fixed Hardware (FFH) Interface", or a platform-independent hardware programming model which relies on platform-specific ACPI Machine Language (AML) provided by the original equipment manufacturer (OEM).
[src:fwupd/acpi] Function Fixed Hardware interfaces are platform-specific features, provided by platform manufacturers for the purposes of performance and failure recovery.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Standard Intel-based PCs have a fixed function interface defined by Intel, which provides a set of core functionality that reduces an ACPI-compliant system's need for full driver stacks for providing basic functionality during boot time or in the case of major system failure.
[src:fwupd/acpi] ACPI Platform Error Interface (APEI) is a specification for reporting of hardware errors, e.g. chipset, RAM to the operating system.
[src:fwupd/acpi] ACPI defines many tables that provide the interface between an ACPI-compliant operating system and system firmware (BIOS or UEFI).
[src:fwupd/acpi] This includes RSDP, RSDT, XSDT, FADT, FACS, DSDT, SSDT, MADT, and MCFG, for example.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The tables allow description of system hardware in a platform-independent manner, and are presented as either fixed-formatted data structures or in AML.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The main AML table is the DSDT (differentiated system description table).
[src:fwupd/acpi] The AML can be decompiled by tools like Intel's iASL (open-source, part of ACPICA) for purposes like patching the tables for expanding OS compatibility.
[src:fwupd/acpi] The Root System Description Pointer (RSDP) is located in a platform-dependent manner, and describes the rest of the tables.
[src:fwupd/acpi] A custom ACPI table called the Windows Platform Binary Table (WPBT) is used by Microsoft to allow vendors to add software into the Windows OS automatically.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Lenovo have been caught using this feature to install harmful software such as Superfish.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Also, Gigabyte Technology have been found using this feature to install its OEM software.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Samsung shipped PCs with Windows Update disabled.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Windows versions older than Windows 7 do not support this feature, but alternative techniques can be used.
[src:fwupd/acpi] This behavior has been compared to rootkits.
[src:fwupd/acpi] Ubuntu founder Mark Shuttleworth says ACPI is a security risk.
[src:fwupd/acpi] He says "arguing for ACPI on your next-generation device is arguing for a trojan horse of monumental proportions to be installed in your living room and in your data centre" and "firmware on your device is the NSA's best friend".
[src:fwupd/acpi] In November 2003, Linus Torvalds—author of the Linux kernel—described ACPI as "a complete design disaster in every way".
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The company started as a manufacturer of complete motherboards, positioning itself in the high-end segment.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Its first customer was PC's Limited, later known as Dell.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] As hardware activity moved progressively to Taiwan-based ODMs, AMI continued to develop BIOS firmware for major motherboard manufacturers.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The company produced BIOS software for motherboards (1986), server motherboards (1992), storage controllers (1995) and remote management cards (1998).
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] In 1993, AMI produced MegaRAID, a storage controller card.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMI sold its RAID assets to LSI in 2001, with only one employee from the RAID-division remaining with the AMI core team.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMI continued to focus on OEM and ODM business and technology.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] From 2019 to 2026, HGGC, a private equity firm, held a significant stake in AMI, including leading the rebrand from American Megatrends to AMI.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] They announced their intent to sell in 2024 and in May 2026, American Megatrends entered into a definitive agreement to be acquired by Lattice Semiconductor for 1.65 billion in a combination of cash and stock.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] (AMI) was founded in 1985 by Subramonian Shankar and Pat Sarma with funds from a previous consulting venture, Access Methods Inc.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Access Methods was a company run by Pat Sarma and his partner.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] After Access Methods successfully launched the AMIBIOS, there were legal issues among the owners of the company, resulting in Sarma buying out his partners.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Access Methods still owned the rights to the AMIBIOS.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Sarma had already started a company called Quintessential Consultants Inc.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] (QCI), and later set up an equal partnership with Shankar.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] By this time the AMIBIOS had become established and there was a need to keep the initials AMI.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The partners renamed QCI as American Megatrends, with the same initials as Access Methods; the renamed company then purchased AMIBIOS from Access Methods.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Shankar became the president and Sarma the executive vice-president of this company.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] This partnership continued until 2001, when LSI Logic purchased the RAID Division of American Megatrends; American Megatrends then purchased all shares of the company owned by Sarma, making Shankar the majority owner.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMIDiag is a family of PC diagnostic utilities sold to OEMs only.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The AMIDiag suite was introduced in 1991 and made available for MS-DOS, Microsoft Windows and UEFI platforms.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] It includes both the Windows and DOS PC diagnostics programs.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Later versions of AMIDiag support UEFI, which allows diagnostics to be performed directly on the hardware components, without having to use operating system drivers or facilities.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Aptio V is AMI's current main UEFI firmware product.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Aptio Community Edition is an open source UEFI firmware product.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Aptio 4 is a now-discontinued previous version that has been succeeded by Aptio V.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Aptio is usually used by the PC and server type devices.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] MegaRAC is a product line of BMC firmware packages and formerly service processors providing out-of-band, or lights-out remote management of computer systems.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] These BMCs running MegaRAC firmware packages or service processors operate independently of the operating system status or location, to manage and troubleshoot computers.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMIBIOS is the IBM PC-compatible BIOS that was formerly developed and sold by American Megatrends since 1986.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] In 1994, the company claimed that 75% of PC clones used AMIBIOS.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] It is used on motherboards made by AMI and by other companies.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] American Megatrends had a strict OEM business model for AMIBIOS: it sold source code to motherboard manufacturers or customized AMIBIOS for each OEM individually, whichever business model they require.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMI does not sell to end users, and itself produces no end-user documentation or technical support for its BIOS firmware, leaving that to licensees.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] However, the company published two books on its BIOS in 1993 and 1994, written by its engineers.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] During powerup, the BIOS firmware displays an ID string in the lower-left-hand corner of the screen.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] This ID string comprises various pieces of information about the firmware, including when it was compiled, what configuration options were selected, the OEM license code, and the targeted chipset and motherboard.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] There are 3 ID string formats, the first for older AMIBIOS, and the second and third for the newer AMI Hi-Flex ("high flexibility") BIOS.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] These latter are displayed when the Insert key is pressed during power-on self-test.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The original AMI BIOS did not encrypt the machine startup password, which it stored in non-volatile RAM.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Therefore, any utility capable of reading a PC's NVRAM was able to read and to alter the password.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The AMI WinBIOS encrypts the stored password, using a simple substitution cipher.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] By pressing the Delete key during power-on self-test when a prompt is displayed, the BIOS setup utility program is invoked.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Some earlier AMIBIOS versions also included a cut-down version of the AMIDIAG utility that AMI also sold separately, but most later AMI BIOSes do not include this program as the BIOS DMI already incorporates detailed diagnostics.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMIBIOS was formerly sold through distributors, not directly available from the manufacturer or from eSupport.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMI supplies both DOS and Windows firmware upgrade utilities for its own motherboards. eSupport only supplies a Windows upgrade utility.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The StorTrends family of network-based backup and storage management software and hardware includes several NAS and iSCSI-based SAN servers with 4, 12, or 16 drive bays.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] AMI couples off-the-shelf hardware with the StorTrends iTX storage management firmware platform.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] StorTrends offers synchronous, asynchronous and snap-assisted replication, thin provisioning, high-availability grouping and advanced caching.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Reliability and performance is the key for any storage server.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] StorTrends iTX 2.8 is designed to support Storage Bridge Bay specification that provide Auto-Failover capability to ensure that any interruption is handled without affecting data.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] It supports High-availability cluster, redundancy, scalability, replication, disaster recovery and multiple site backups.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Because DuOS-M has the capability to run both Windows and Android simultaneously, the user can switch between the two operating systems without having to dual boot or suspend operation of one operating system in order to utilize the other.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] DuOS-M supports key hardware peripherals in Windows including cameras, audio, microphone and sensors such as ambient light sensor, accelerometer, gyrometer, compass and orientation sensors.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] It also supports various screen sizes, resolutions, and screen orientation (portrait and landscape) along with 3D acceleration and HD video playback.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The first version of DuOS-M was released in June 2014.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The software is available for download for a free 30-day trial, and is available for purchase for a complete license.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] On March 7, 2018, American Megatrends officially announced that it ceased development of DuOS-M.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] No further updates were being released at this time, including bug fixes and security patches.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] On November 13, 1993, some PCs with AMIBIOS firmware began bootup playing the tune to "Happy Birthday".
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The PC would remain halted, and the song would continue playing until a key was pressed, after which bootup would resume.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The problem was caused by a virus-free Trojan, which was later resolved with firmware updates.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The AMI WinBIOS was a 1994 update to AMIBIOS, with a GUI setup screen that mimicked the appearance of Windows 3.1 and supported mouse navigation, unusual at the time.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] WinBIOS was viewed favorably by Anand Lal Shimpi at AnandTech, but described by Thomas Pabst at Tom's Hardware as a "big disappointment", in part because of problems with distributing IRQ signals to every PCI and ISA expansion slot.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] In July 2008 Linux developers discovered issues with ACPI tables on certain AMIBIOS BIOSes supplied by Foxconn, ASUS, and MSI.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The problem was related to the ACPI _OSI method, which is used by ACPI to determine the OS version (in case an ACPI patch only applies to one specific OS).
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] In some cases, the OSI method caused problems on Linux systems, skipping code that was only executed on Windows systems.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Foxconn and AMI worked together to develop a solution, which was included in later revisions of AMIBIOS.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] The issue affected motherboards with Intel Socket 775.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] Actual system behavior differed based on BIOS version, system hardware and Linux distribution.
[src:fwupd/ami-aptio] In October 2021 an issue was discovered where some Baseboard Management Controllers were shipped with a license/royalty sticker that had the company name misspelled as "American Megatrands".
[src:fwupd/apt-rpm] In March 2005, the maintainer of the program, Gustavo Niemeyer, announced that he would not continue developing it and that he would instead focus on **Smart Package Manager**, which was planned as a successor to APT-RPM.
[src:fwupd/apt-rpm] In March 2006, development was picked up again by Panu Matilainen from Red Hat at a new home, introducing basic multilib functionality and support for common repository metadata.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT is a collection of tools distributed in a package named *apt*.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] A significant part of APT is defined in a C++ library of functions; APT also includes command-line programs for dealing with packages, which use the library.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] Three such programs are `apt`, `apt-get` and `apt-cache`.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] They are commonly used in examples because they are simple and ubiquitous.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] The *apt* package is of "*important*" priority in all current Debian releases, and is therefore included in a default Debian installation.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT can be considered a front end to `dpkg`, friendlier than the older `dselect` front end.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] While `dpkg` performs actions on individual packages, APT manages relations (especially dependencies) between them, as well as sourcing and management of higher-level versioning decisions such as release tracking and Upgrade Suppression.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT is often hailed as one of Debian's best features, which Debian developers attribute to the strict quality controls in Debian's policy.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] A major feature of APT is the way it calls `dpkg` –it performs topological sorting of the list of packages to be installed or removed and calls `dpkg` in the best possible sequence.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] In some cases, it utilizes the `--force` options of `dpkg`.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] However, it only does this when it is unable to calculate how to avoid the reason `dpkg` requires the action to be forced.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] The user indicates one or more packages to be installed.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] Each package name is phrased as just the name portion of the package, not a fully qualified filename (for instance, in a Debian system, `libc6` would be the argument provided, not `libc6_1.9.6-2.deb`).
[src:fwupd/apt-software] Notably, APT automatically gets and installs packages upon which the indicated package depends (if necessary).
[src:fwupd/apt-software] This was an original distinguishing characteristic of APT-based package management systems, as it avoided installation failure due to missing dependencies, a type of dependency hell.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] Another distinction is the retrieval of packages from remote repositories.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT uses a location configuration file (`/etc/apt/sources.list`) to locate the desired packages, which might be available on the network or a removable storage medium, for example, and retrieve them, and also obtain information about available (but not installed) packages.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT provides other command options to override decisions made by apt-get's conflict resolution system.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] One option is to force a particular version of a package.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] This can downgrade a package and render dependent software inoperable, so the user must be careful.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] Finally, the `apt_preferences` mechanism allows the user to create an alternative installation policy for individual packages.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] The user can specify packages using a POSIX regular expression.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT searches its cached list of packages and lists the dependencies that must be installed or updated.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] APT retrieves, configures and installs the dependencies automatically.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] Triggers are the treatment of deferred actions.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] `/etc/apt` contains the APT configuration folders and files.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] `apt-config` is the APT Configuration Query program.
[src:fwupd/apt-software] `apt-config dump` shows the configuration.
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] Although ACE went defunct, and no computer was ever manufactured which fully complied with the ARC standard, the ARC system has a widespread legacy in that all operating systems in the Windows NT family use ARC conventions for naming boot devices.
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] SGI's modified version of the ARC firmware is named ARCS.
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] All SGI computers which run IRIX 6.1 or later, such as the Indy and Octane, boot from an ARCS console, which uses the same drive naming conventions as Windows.
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] Most of the various RISC-based computers designed to run Windows NT have versions of the ARC boot console to boot NT.
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] It was predicted that Intel IA-32-based computers would adopt the ARC console, although only SGI ever marketed such machines with ARC firmware (namely, the SGI Visual Workstation series, which launched in 1999).
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] Compared to UEFI, the ARC firmware also included support for FAT, boot variables, C-calling interface.
[src:fwupd/arc-specification] It did not include the same level of extensibility as UEFI and the same level of governance like with the UEFI Forum.
[src:fwupd/boot] In Unix-like operating systems, a **boot folder** is the directory which holds files used in booting the operating system, typically /boot.
[src:fwupd/boot] The usage is standardized within Linux in the Filesystem Hierarchy Standard.
[src:fwupd/boot] The contents are mostly Linux kernel files or boot loader files, depending on the boot loader, most commonly (on Linux) LILO or GRUB.
[src:fwupd/boot] LILO may also use other files, such as message and also stores a non-boot configuration file in /etc/lilo.conf.
[src:fwupd/boot] GRUB stores its files in the subdirectory grub/ (i.e. /boot/grub/).
[src:fwupd/boot] These files are mostly modules (.mod), with configuration stored in grub.cfg.
[src:fwupd/boot] /boot/ is often simply a directory on the main (or only) hard drive partition.
[src:fwupd/boot] However, it may be a separate partition.
[src:fwupd/boot] A separate partition is generally only used when bootloaders are incapable of reading the main filesystem (e.g.
[src:fwupd/boot] LILO does not recognize XFS) or other problems not easily resolvable by users.
[src:fwupd/boot] On UEFI systems, including most modern PCs, the EFI system partition is often mounted at /boot/, /efi/ or /boot/efi/.
[src:fwupd/fwupd] The Linux Vendor Firmware Service (LVFS) provides resources and support for helping vendors package their firmware updates to support the use of this framework, and serves as an online repository for obtaining these updates.
[src:fwupd/fwupd] To provide a test case on systems where ESRT is not yet supported, fwupd is also able to update firmware on the ColorHug color calibrator.
[src:fwupd/fwupd] In December 2015, it was revealed that Hughes had been working with a Dell developer to test the system on actual hardware, and that its Dell Edge Gateway product will support firmware servicing via fwupd.
[src:fwupd/fwupd] Hughes reported that the company was also "considering expanding out the LVFS support to all new models supporting UEFI updates".
[src:fwupd/fwupd] In August 2018, Lenovo joined the project and provides update support for a wide range of their devices.
[src:fwupd/fwupd] In September 2019, Acer joined the project, with initial support for their Aspire A315 model.
[src:fwupd/fwupd] Starting from December 2019, Google requires that firmware updates can be applied with fwupd for certified Chromebooks.
